subSection.paragraph:
The Sarcophagidae ( Diptera ) or flesh flies is a cosmopolitan family of oestroid calyptrates (
Yan et al. 2021b
) comprising more than 3100 described species currently assigned to about 175 genera, which are classified in three subfamilies: Miltogramminae, Paramacronychiinae and Sarcophaginae (
Pape et al . 2011
; Evenhuis & Pape 2022 ). The family is biologically diverse and has its peak diversity in warm tropical areas ( Pape 1996 ,
Yan et al. 2021a
). The family is well defined through the possession of a bilobed incubatory pouch from the common oviduct, but the lack of conspicuous synapomorphies in adult external morphology makes Sarcophagidae difficult to key out, and they are often identified from the individual subfamilies (
Buck et al . 2009
), or through a complex combination of character states (
Marshall et al . 2017
). For most species, only males can be reliably identified to species based on morphology (e.g., Xue & Chao 1996 ; Kurahashi & Kakinuma 2015 ;
Souza et al . 2020
;
Kurahashi et al . 2021
) and often only after examination of the terminalia. Identification based on molecular data is still mainly feasible for species of forensic importance (
Boehme et al . 2012
;
Oliveira et al . 2017
;
Samerjai et al. 2020
;
Sonet et al . 2013
) although molecular ‘barcode’ libraries are rapidly accumulating (e.g., Ratnasingham & Hebert 2013 ;
Moriniére et al. 2019
;
Chang et al . 2020
;
Fuentes-Lopez et al. 2021
). Other methods of identification are showing some promise, like cuticular hydrocarbons (
Moore et al. 2021
, 2022 ) and wing venation patterns (
Szpila et al. 2022
;
Ling et al. 2023
), but these are still under development.

All sarcophagids are ovoviviparous, depositing newly-hatched first instar larvae, or more rarely incubated eggs with mature first instar larvae ready to hatch ( Marshall 2012 ). The larvae of most Miltogramminae are kleptoparasites in the nests of aculeate wasps ( Hymenoptera : Aculeata), but several are necrophagous or sarcosaprophagous feeding on buried carrion (
Piwczyński et al. 2017
). The immature sarcophaginae are frequently involved in forensic investigations as entomological evidence found mostly during the first and second instar or throughout the decomposition of ephemeral corpses and carcasses ( Smith 1986 ; Avila & Goff 1998 ; Byrd & Butler 1998 ;
Barros et al . 2008
;
Alves et al . 2014
). The adult sarcophagids are usually attracted to odours of decay or to nectar ( Byrd & Castner 2001 ;
Roziah et al . 2015
). Some species of both Paramacronychiinae and Sarcophaginae are obligatory parasites or predators of invertebrates, and others breed as scavengers in dead or dying animals. Some Sarcophaginae have been reared from dung, but in such cases it is possible that the larval food was not the substrate but the insects it contained ( Deeming 1995 ).

Photographs of 

Hoplacephala transfuga
(Villeneuve)

were taken using a BK plus Imaging System from Visionary Digital™ (Palmyra, PA, 
USA
) equipped with a Canon 7D digital camera (in 
NHMDK
). Stacks of images from multiple focal planes were combined using Zerene Stacker (Zerene Systems LLC).All other photographs were taken using a Canon EOS 8OD DSLR camera attached to a Leica Z6 Macroscope with trinocular head (in 
NMWC
). Images were stacked using HeliconFocus v6.22. (HeliconSoft Ltd) extended depth of field software. Calibrated scale bars were added using Adobe Photoshop v.21. Figures for the new species were drawn using a Wild binocular microscope with a camera lucida.

